# Coding Style Rules

## General Principles

- Prefer concise, readable code over verbose explanations
- Eliminate unnecessary intermediate variables when the logic can be expressed inline
- Use simple default values where appropriate (`||`, `??`) — not extra defensive branches (see no-unprompted-defensive-fallbacks)
- Consolidate related logic into single expressions when it improves readability

## JavaScript/TypeScript Patterns

### Variable Elimination

- Remove intermediate variables when the value is only used once
- Prefer inline expressions over separate variable declarations

### Conditional Logic Simplification

- Prefer one-line `if` when the body is a single statement
- Consolidate multi-line conditional logic into single expressions when possible
- Use logical operators (`||`, `&&`, `??`) for simple fallbacks

### Default Values

- Prefer inline fallbacks over separate conditional blocks when the logic stays clear
- Example: `(offset ?? 0)` instead of a multi-line undefined check

### Mathematical Expressions

- Use underscores in large numbers for readability (e.g. `60_000`)

## Code Structure Preferences

### Server actions & forms

- Keep request parsing minimal
- Handle optional fields with inline fallbacks when obvious
- Read honeypot / form fields from `FormData` at submit time rather than lifting state unnecessarily

### React Components

- Eliminate duplicate state when one value or a single enum (`step`) can represent the flow
- Use direct function calls in event handlers when the logic is simple
- Prefer concise prop passing over intermediate variables

## Readability Guidelines

- When a single expression can replace multiple lines of conditional logic, prefer the single expression — unless it hurts clarity
- Use descriptive variable names, but don't create variables just for the sake of naming
- Balance conciseness with clarity - if an inline expression becomes too complex, break it out

### Comments

- Avoid comments that simply restate what each line of code does
- Prefer comments that explain intent, trade-offs, constraints, or layout/section structure
- Short JSX block comments that mark logical sections are fine in large components

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- Creating variables that are only used once
- Multi-line conditional blocks that can be expressed as single expressions
- Unnecessary intermediate steps in simple calculations
- Splitting one conceptual state into multiple booleans when an enum is clearer
